This airplane model is manufactured in Canada and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is type certificated for operation in the United States 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the provisions of &sect;21.29 of the Federal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Aviation Regulations and the applicable bilateral 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
airworthiness agreement. Pursuant to this bilateral 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
airworthiness agreement, Transport Canada has kept the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
FAA informed of the situation described above. The FAA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
has examined the findings of Transport Canada, reviewed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
all available information, and determined that AD 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
action is necessary for products of this type design 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that are certificated for operation in the United 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Since an unsafe condition has been identified that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is likely to exist or develop in other de Havilland DHC-6 series airplanes of the same type design, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed AD would require repetitively inspecting the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
horizontal stabilizer center hinge bracket for cracks, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and replacing any cracked center hinge bracket. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposed action would be accomplished in accordance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with the ACCOMPLISHMENT INSTRUCTIONS section of de 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Havilland SB 6/512, dated October 25, 1991. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The FAA estimates that 169 airplanes in the U.S. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
registry would be affected by the proposed AD, that it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would take approximately 1 workhour per airplane to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
accomplish the proposed inspection, and that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
average labor rate is approximately $55 an hour. Based 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on these figures, the total cost impact of the proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
AD on U.S. operators is estimated to be $9,295. This 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
figure only includes the cost for the initial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inspection and does not include replacement costs if a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
center hinge bracket was found cracked nor does it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
include repetitive inspection costs. The FAA has no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
way to determine how many center hinge brackets may be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cracked or how many repetitive inspections each 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
owner/operator may incur. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The regulations proposed herein would not have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
substantial direct effects on the States, on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
relationship between the national government and the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States, or on the distribution of power and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsibilities among the various levels of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
government. Therefore, in accordance with Executive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Order 12612, it is determined that this proposal would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not have sufficient federalism implications to warrant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the preparation of a Federalism Assessment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For the reasons discussed above, I certify that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this action (1) is not a ``significant regulatory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
action'' under Executive Order 12866; (2) is not a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``significant rule'' under DOT Regulatory Policies and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Procedures (44 FR 11034, February 26, 1979); and (3) if 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
promulgated, will not have a significant economic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impact, positive or negative, on a substantial number 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of small entities under the criteria of the Regulatory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
