<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940217-1-00055 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940217-1-00013 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 2: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Several individuals questioned the taxonomic status 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the salamander, asserting that it is still an undescribed species 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and may be part of the central Texas salamander (
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Eurycea neotenes
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
complex. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Formal description of the salamander as a distinct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
species has withstood peer-review and was published in June, 1993 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(see discussion in the Background section). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 3: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Several commenters stated that water quality data at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Barton Springs show no demonstrable deterioration, despite 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
development immediately upstream from the springs, much of which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
occurred prior to implementation of water quality controls. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Service recognizes that, other than high levels 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of fecal-group bacteria and turbidity immediately following storm 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
events, water quality at Barton Springs is considered to be very 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
good. However, only about 3 to 4 percent of the recharge and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contributing zones is currently developed. As urban development 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
over the recharge and contributing zones increases, the threat of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
water quality degradation from point-source and non-point-source 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pollution will increase. The threat of increased urbanization over 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these areas and impacts on water quality in the aquifer and at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Barton Springs are discussed in Factor A. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 4: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Most commenters opposed to the listing stated that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
existing State and local rules and regulations are adequate to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
protect the salamander and its habitat from groundwater degradation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and depletion. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This issue is presented and discussed in Factor D. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Service recognizes that there are several rules and regulations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
aimed at protecting water quality and quantity within the aquifer, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and that these rules and regulations will provide some benefits to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Barton Springs salamander if adequately enforced. However, no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
information was presented to show that these existing rules and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations will ensure long-term protection of water quality and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quantity at Barton Springs and will be adequate to protect the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
salamander and its habitat. Furthermore, there are no assurances 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that the existing rules and regulations will remain in place and be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
enforced. Regarding water quantity, the Barton Springs/Edwards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Aquifer Conservation District (BS/EACD) has limited enforcement 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
authority and does not regulate 30 to 40 percent of the total volume 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that is pumped from the Barton Springs segment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 5: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Several individuals expressed concern that listing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the salamander could impose restrictions on the recreational use of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Barton Springs Pool. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This issue is discussed under Factor B 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(``Overutilization for commercial, recreational, scientific, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
educational purposes''). There is currently no evidence suggesting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that swimming in Barton Springs Pool will adversely impact the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Barton Springs salamander. The Service maintains the position that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
if pool maintenance activities are conducted in such a way as to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
avoid impacting the salamander and its habitat (such as avoiding the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
application of chemicals and the use of high pressure fire hoses to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
clean areas inhabited by salamanders), then activities associated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with swimming at Barton Springs Pool should not disturb the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
salamander. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 6: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The salamander has persisted despite past droughts, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
low springflows, and pollution events over the aquifer and its 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contributing zone and at Barton Springs (elevated fecal coliform 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bacteria and turbidity). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Service acknowledges that these events have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
occurred and that the frequency of such events is likely to increase 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with increasing development over the aquifer and its contributing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
zone. Although the salamander has survived these past events, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
point at which declining water quality and quantity would cause 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
extinction of the salamander is uncertain. Amphibians in general 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are highly sensitive to changes in water chemistry, and the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
salamander's restricted range makes it especially vulnerable to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
water quality deterioration. A major pollution event has the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
potential of eliminating the entire species and/or its prey base. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Amphipods, which comprise most of the salamander's diet, are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
especially sensitive to water pollution (see discussion in Factor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
E). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Issue 7: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
A few commenters stated that the threat of declining 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
aquifer levels is not substantial at Barton Springs and, in any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
event, no demonstrable evidence exists that lowered aquifer levels 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
will cause a threat to the continued existence of the salamander. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Response: 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This issue is addressed in Factor A. Although the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Service recognizes that cessation of flows is not likely at Barton 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Springs in the near future, increased groundwater withdrawal and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
resulting reduced flows are expected due to increasing urbanization 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
over the aquifer. Reduced aquifer levels may lead to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
encroachment of the ``bad water'' line and increased concentrations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of pollutants in the aquifer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
