<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940217-1-00061 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940217-1-00013 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
D. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
The inadequacy of existing regulatory mechanisms. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
No 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
existing rules or regulations specifically require protection of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Barton Springs salamander or its habitat. The salamander is not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
included on the TPWD's list of threatened and endangered species, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and thus the species is not afforded protection by that agency. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Several individuals who provided comments on the 90-day finding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
stated that existing state and local regulations are sufficient to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
mitigate potential water quality threats resulting from development 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities in the Barton Springs segment and contributing zone. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
However, while there are many existing rules and regulations in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
place that will likely contribute positively to water quality and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quantity, there are no assurances that they are adequate to protect 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the salamander and its habitat. Furthermore, whether the existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rules and regulations can provide long-term protection of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quality and quantity of the waters feeding Barton Springs is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unknown. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
There are few measures in place to prevent the risk of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hazardous material spills across the recharge and contributing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
zones. No regulations prohibit the transportation of hazardous 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
materials across the Barton Springs segment (Tom Word, Texas 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Department of Transportation (TxDOT), pers. comm., 1993), and few 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
existing roads have water quality control structures (such as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hazardous materials traps, sediment basins, and filters) to protect 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
against non-point-source pollution and chemical spills (Shyra Darr, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Travis County Public Improvements and Transportation Department 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(PITD), 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993; Barnett, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993; Roland Gamble, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
TxDOT, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). Travis County and TxDOT have agreed to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
install water quality devices on new State and county roadway 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
construction projects in the recharge zone (Barnett, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
David Pimentel, PITD, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993; Gamble, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
However, no program is currently in place to retrofit these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
water quality control structures on existing roadways in the Barton 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Springs segment (Barnett, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). In addition, the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effectiveness of these water quality control structures has not yet 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
been determined (Gamble, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The major regulations affecting water quality in the Barton 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Springs segment include the Edwards Rules (31 Texas Administrative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Code, Chapter 313), which are promulgated and enforced by the TWC, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the City of Austin's water quality protective ordinances 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(Williamson Creek Ordinance (1980), Barton Creek Watershed Ordinance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1981), Lower Watersheds Ordinance (1981), Comprehensive Watersheds 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Ordinance (1986), ``Composite Ordinance'' (1991), and the ``Save Our 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Springs'' (``SOS'') Ordinance (1992)). These ordinances are only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
implemented within Austin's city limits and five-mile 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
extra-territorial jurisdiction, which is about a third of the entire 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
area affecting Barton Springs. Each ordinance includes impervious 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cover limitations, development setbacks from water quality zones, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
erosion control measures, restricted or prohibited development on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
steep slopes, and other water quality protective measures. However, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
none of the ordinances include retrofit provisions for existing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
developments or land use regulations (Barnett, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Furthermore, the ordinances can be rendered ineffective by variance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provisions and exemptions. The SOS Ordinance requires greater 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
impervious cover limitations, further development restrictions in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the water quality zones of Barton Creek, and limitations of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exemptions from the ordinance provisions, and will attempt to reduce 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the risk of accidental contamination (Barnett, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
in litt., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
1993). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Edwards Rules regulate construction-related activities on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the recharge zone that may ``alter or disturb the topographic, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
geologic, or existing recharge characteristics of a site'' as well 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as any other activity ``which may pose a potential for contaminating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Edwards Aquifer,'' including sewage collection systems and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hazardous materials storage tanks. The Edwards Rules regulate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
construction activities through review of Water Pollution Abatement 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Plans (WPAPs). The WPAPs do not require site-specific water quality 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
performance standards for developments over the recharge zone nor do 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
they address land use, impervious cover limitations, or retrofitting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for developments existing prior to the implementation of the Rules. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(Travis County was not incorporated into the Rules until March, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1990; Hays County was incorporated in 1984.) The WPAPs also do not 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulate development activities in the aquifer's contributing zone. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
As yet, the Edwards Rules do not include a comprehensive plan to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
address the effects of cumulative impacts on water quality in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
aquifer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
