<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
These provisions would expand the factors of financial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsibility of an institution to take into consideration 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
substantial control over both other existing institutions (as opposed to only defunct institutions) and third-party
servicers. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 498(e) of the HEA clearly contemplates this expansion. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Furthermore, these requirements are needed for the same reasons 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that similar requirements recently were adopted for persons with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
substantial control over defunct institutions. A person might be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsible for incurring liabilities for Title IV, HEA program 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violations because of his or her substantial control over 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicers or other institutions. The person could, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
nevertheless, have the same level of control over a participating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institution while avoiding responsibility for repayment of those 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
liabilities. These requirements are intended to prevent those 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
persons from continuing to participate either directly or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
indirectly in the Title IV, HEA programs without assuming 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsibility for their prior actions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Secretary also proposes technical changes to this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section to remove as factors of financial responsibility the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consideration of matters that would instead be included in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&sect;668.12 as conditions for participation in the Title IV, HEA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
programs, for the reasons given in the discussion of that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Section 668.23&blank;Audits, records, and examination.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Secretary proposes to specify that in addition to current 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements, an institution would be required to cooperate with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a guaranty agency in whose program the institution participates 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the State postsecondary review entity designated under 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subpart 1 of part H of Title IV of the HEA, in the conduct 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of audits, investigations, and program reviews. These requirements 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would clarify existing responsibilities to be accountable to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
authorized persons or organizations for the institution's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities with respect to the sound management of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Title IV, HEA programs. The Secretary further proposes to apply 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these requirements to a third-party servicer that contracts with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
an institution to administer any aspect of that institution's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
participation in a Title IV, HEA program. This change would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
merely clarify existing responsibilities of a third-party 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer, as an agent of an institution, to be accountable and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provide access to authorized persons for the servicer's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
activities on behalf of the institution's participation in a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Title IV, HEA program. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Secretary proposes to add a requirement that a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicer that administers funds or determines student 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
eligibility under contract with an institution would be required 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to have prepared, at least annually, a compliance audit of all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
aspects of the servicer's administration of the participation in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Title IV, HEA programs of each institution with which the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer contracts. (This requirement would be satisfied by an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
audit report submitted in accordance with the Single Audit Act or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Office of Management and Budget Circular A&hyph;133.) This 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement is necessitated by section 487(c)(1)(C) of the HEA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Secretary, however, believes that the contractual 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
obligations of some third-party servicers do not necessitate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
audits of the servicers' activities. Accordingly, the Secretary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposes to require annual audits to be performed only by those 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicers that administer funds or determine student eligibility 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on behalf of institutions. The consequences of the activities of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
those servicers to the integrity of the Title IV, HEA programs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
justify stricter accountability to the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition, the Secretary proposes certain additional 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exceptions to the annual audit requirement in the discussion that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
follows. A third-party servicer that is required to have an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
audit performed would be excused from the annual audit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement if that servicer contracts with only one 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
participating institution and if that servicer's administration 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of a Title IV, HEA program would still be covered fully in that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institution's compliance audit. (In proposed regulations to be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
published shortly after these, the Secretary intends to propose 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to excuse certain institutions from having an annual audit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
performed. If an institution were to be excused from an audit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirement, the activities of that institution's third-party 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer would not be fully covered, and thus the servicer would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be required to have an audit performed to meet the requirements 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of this section). This provision would not harm the integrity of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Title IV, HEA programs as the servicer's activities still 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would be covered fully by the submission of an institution's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
compliance audit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A third-party servicer that is required to have an audit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
performed and that contracts with more than one participating 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institution could have performed, to meet the requirements of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this section, a single comprehensive compliance audit that covers all of the servicer's activities for all of the
institutions that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the servicer contracts with for Title IV, HEA program purposes, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
if the audit is conducted in such a way as to satisfy each 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
individual audit requirement and if the audit covers all aspects 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the servicer's administration of the participation in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Title IV, HEA programs of all institutions with which the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer contracts. The Secretary believes that, by allowing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicers to have one inclusive audit performed, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
instead of many individual audits, the burden associated with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
these regulations would be reduced (regulatory burden reduction 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is an objective under Executive Order (E.O.) 12866). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Furthermore, the Secretary does not believe that this provision 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would in any way affect the soundness of the information required 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
by these regulations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
