<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Secretary proposes that if a determination is made to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assess a liability against a third-party servicer, the servicer 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would be required to notify each institution under whose contract 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the servicer was assessed a liability of the Secretary's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determination. The servicer would also be required to notify 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
every institution that contracts with the servicer for the same 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
service that the Secretary determined a liability is owed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Final consensus on this particular language was not reached 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as negotiators believed that this provision essentially requires 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the notification of all institutions with which a servicer 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contracts. Negotiators objected to a notice being provided to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institutions that a servicer contracts with that would not be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
directly affected by a determination from the Secretary to assess 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
liability. A number of negotiators opposed this language on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ground that such a blanket notification unnecessarily damages a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer's reputation among unaffected institutions. However, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Secretary believes that an institution that contracts with a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicer should be informed of determinations by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Department of Education that the institution's servicer is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
improperly administering the Title IV, HEA programs, especially 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
given the potential liability exposure to the institution. These 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
notification requirements would arise only if the Secretary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determines that a third-party servicer owes a liability based on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
an audit finding, after providing the institution or third-party 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer an opportunity to respond to an audit report response. By limiting the requirement for notice provided by
a third-party 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
servicer to institutions receiving the same service for which a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
liability was assessed, the Secretary believes that he has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responded to any legitimate concerns raised by the negotiators. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Section 668.25 Contracts between an institution and a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicer.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Secretary proposes to redesignate &sect;668.25, governing loss of institutional eligibility, as &sect;668.26

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and to add a new &sect;668.25 that would establish minimum 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements for contracts between an institution and a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
third-party servicer. Proposed &sect;668.25 would allow an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
institution to contract with a servicer to administer aspects of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the institution's participation in a Title IV, HEA program only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to the extent that the servicer's eligibility to contract with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that institution has not been limited, suspended, or terminated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the proceedings in Subpart G (as proposed to be amended). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition, under these proposed regulations, a third-party 
